1 (2) A unit of local government that imposed a local transient lodging tax on July 1, 2003, may
2 not increase the rate of the local transient lodging tax on or after July 2, 2003, to a rate that is
3 greater than the rate in effect on July 1, 2003, unless the increase was approved on or before July
4 1, 2003.
5 (3) A unit of local government that imposed a local transient lodging tax on July 1, 2003, may
6 not decrease the percentage of total local transient lodging tax revenues that are actually expended
7 to fund tourism promotion or tourism-related facilities on or after July 2, 2003. A unit of local gov-
8 ernment that agreed, on or before July 1, 2003, to increase the percentage of total local transient
9 lodging tax revenues that are to be expended to fund tourism promotion or tourism-related facilities,
10 must increase the percentage as agreed.
11 (4) Notwithstanding subsections (1) and (2) of this section, a unit of local government that is fi-
12 nancing debt with local transient lodging tax revenues on November 26, 2003, must continue to fi-
13 nance the debt until the retirement of the debt, including any refinancing of that debt. If the tax is
14 not otherwise permitted under subsection (1) or (2) of this section, at the time of the debt retirement:
15 (a) The local transient lodging tax revenue that financed the debt shall be used as provided in
16 subsection (5) of this section; or
17 (b) The unit of local government shall thereafter eliminate the new tax or increase in tax oth-
18 erwise described in subsection (1) or (2) of this section.
19 (5) Subsections (1) and (2) of this section do not apply to a new or increased local transient
20 lodging tax if all of the net revenue from the new or increased tax, following reductions attributed
21 to collection reimbursement charges, is used consistently with subsection (6) of this section to:
22 (a) Fund tourism promotion or tourism-related facilities;
23 (b) Fund city or county services, whether emergency or nonemergency services, provided
24 directly by the city or county or by a special district in lieu of the city or county; or
25 (c) Finance or refinance the debt of tourism-related facilities and pay reasonable administrative
26 costs incurred in financing or refinancing that debt, provided that:
27 (A) The net revenue may be used for administrative costs only if the unit of local government
28 provides a collection reimbursement charge; and
29 (B) Upon retirement of the debt, the unit of local government reduces the tax by the amount
30 by which the tax was increased to finance or refinance the debt.
31 (6)(a) At least [70] 50 percent of net revenue from a new or increased local transient lodging
32 tax shall be used for the purposes described in subsection (5)(a) or (c) of this section.
33 (b) No more than [30] 50 percent of net revenue from a new or increased local transient lodging
34 tax may be used for the purpose described in subsection (5)(b) of this section.
35 (7)(a) Notwithstanding subsection (1) of this section, a unit of local government may use
36 unexpended net revenue collected before the effective date of this 2026 Act from a new tax
37 described in subsection (1) of this section in accordance with subsection (6) of this section.
38 (b) Notwithstanding subsection (2) of this section, a unit of local government may use
39 unexpended net revenue collected before the effective date of this 2026 Act that is attribut-
40 able to the rate of the local transient lodging tax in effect on July 1, 2003, and to any increase
41 in the rate made on or after July 2, 2003, in accordance with subsection (6) of this section.
42 (c) Notwithstanding subsection (3) of this section, a unit of local government may, in
43 accordance with subsection (6) of this section, decrease the percentage of total local tran-
44 sient lodging tax revenues that are actually expended to fund tourism promotion or
45 tourism-related facilities regardless of when the percentage went into effect.
